many’s historic traditions and the ideals of German culture, the isolation, exile and persecution of Jewish musicians by the Nazis became an act of musical self-mutilation.Michael Haas looks at the actual contribution of Jewish composers in Germany and Austria before 1933, at their increasingly precarious position in Nazi Europe, their forced emigration before and during the war, their ambivalent relationships with their countries of refuge, such as Britain and the United States and their contributions within the radically changed post-war music environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aComposerszGermany. 0aJewish composers. 0aJewish musicianszAustriaxHistory. 0aJewish musicianszGermanyxHistory. 0aMusic by Jewish composerszAustriaxHistory and criticism. 0aMusic by Jewish composerszGermanyxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030015430640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015431340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300154313423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300154313/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY